summary: Two new boards were added this month, Euphoria and Brie Larson! Euphoria is an upcoming American teen drama television series...
caption:
Two new boards were added this month, Euphoria and Brie Larson!

Euphoria is an upcoming American teen drama television series created by Sam Levinson, based on the Israeli series of the same name. It is set to premiere on HBO on June 16, 2019.

The show follows a group of high school students as they navigate drugs, sex, identity, trauma, social media, love and friendship.

The main cast includes Zendaya, Hunter Schafer, Jacob Elordi, Algee Smith, Maude Apatow, Sydney Sweeney, Barbie Ferreira, Storm Reid, and Eric Dane!

Brie Larson is an American actress and filmmaker. Noted for her supporting work in comedies when a teenager, she has since expanded to leading roles in independent dramas and film franchises, receiving such accolades as an Academy Award and a Golden Globe. Time magazine named her one of the 100 most influential people in the world in 2019.

Brie’s breakthrough came with a leading role in the acclaimed independent drama Short Term 12 (2013), and she continued to take on supporting parts in the romance The Spectacular Now (2013) and the comedy Trainwreck (2015). For playing a kidnapping victim in the drama Room (2015), Brie won the Academy Award for Best Actress. The 2017 adventure film Kong: Skull Island marked her first big-budget release, after which she starred as Carol Danvers in the 2019 Marvel Cinematic Universe superhero films Captain Marvel and Avengers: Endgame.

summary: Subverting Expectations: Captain Marvel & Wonder Woman
title: Subverting Expectations: Captain Marvel & Wonder Woman
body:
Now that Captain Marvel is finally out on home video and there are good quality copies of clips out there, I can finally point out something I noticed with visual aids. 

One of the things both of these both films have in common is how they subvert, or at least tweak, the common big finale fight. Wonder Woman less so, since for the majority of it is previz big VFX work – there is some artful compositing and color play at least. What makes it work though, besides giving us this image.

Is how it visually undermines and genders the associated spectacle as maculine by emphasizing the destructive elements and showing the lack of fight progress that is created by trying to fight Ares. Diana finishes things when she stops fighting, and turns Ares own attack on himself.


 Captain Marvel does something similar. The big spectacle finale is actually pretty boring visually, most of it is a bunch of long shots that deny character identification. It’s a bunch of explosions and than Captain Marvel floats in front of Ronan with a angry face. That isn’t the finale though since Yon-Rogg is still down there. So of course they must duke it out, and prove that she has grown and all that. And she has, Vers realizes she’s been a party to unjust military action and that the ideology Yon-Rogg and the Kree expose isn’t benevolent imperialism (it’s just imperialism.) So she just blasts Yon-Rogg and sends him on his way.


 Both films undermine the dominant narrative styles of the genre (both blockbuster film and superhero) as expressions of a separate path forward.

Wonder Woman

Directed by Patty Jenkins
Screenplay by Allan Heinberg
Story by Zack Snyder, Allan Heinberg, Jason Fuchs
Cinematography by Matthew Jensen
Edited by Martin Walsh

Captain Marvel

Directed by Anna Boden and Ryan FleckScreenplay by Anna Boden, Ryan Fleck, Geneva Robertson-DworetStory by Nicole Perlman, Meg LeFauve, Anna Boden, Ryan Fleck, Geneva Robertson-DworetCinematography by Ben DavisEdited by Elliot Graham Debbie Berman
